Caddy's shot of the day
A driver shot doesn't necessarily have to be hit off the tee.
On something like the second shot of a par five hole, when you want to gain some distance, there's also the technique known as the "driver off the deck", where you strike the ball where it is on the ground.
Modern drivers have large heads, so they do come with the risk of sending the ball flying off in the wrong direction, but there is a player who practices this technique frequently on the teeing ground.
It's Ikemura Tomoyo, tipped to win his first tour victory.
In his 7th year of professional golf, the 24-year-old has a diminutive stature at 1.66m, but he is currently seventh in terms of driving distance (hitting an average of 304.02 yards).
While long shots are his forte, one of the issues was the precision of the fairway wood.
Then one day in early spring, he was enlightened: "Since the spoon (three wood) shot wasn't working, I thought I would try the driver off the deck."
From the practice round, he would plop the ball down on the grass in the teeing area, and casually swing a driver at it.
At times when a big carry is required, the ball is often teed up, but Ikemura employs the driver off the deck for holes where both sides are narrow.
"It can be used for holes where the line of sight is downhill."
The trajectory tracker records a carry of 270-280 yards.
"So a three wood is not required. The caddy also said that a driver off the deck is safer than a three wood.
Since the Japan Golf Tour Championship in June, the only wood in Ikemura's caddy bag is the driver.
His second longest club is a utility iron with a loft of 17°.
This tactic has astonished his fellow tourmates, but has also caused rousing cheers from the spectators who witness it.
Apparently, the trick is to "swing the club level".
"Whether performing a down blow or an upper, it doesn't fly true. A cut shot will send it to the right. Originally, I was merely using the driver off the deck to correct the swing of the driver shot (when teeing up). This practice also gives it a gentler attack angle (the angle of incidence of the club)."
The ball is not gripped by the head of the club, incurring the risk of slicing it, but it "eliminates the left side (it doesn't curve to the left)."
