How to prevent dementia and keep it at a merely "forgetful" stage?
Interview and story by Watanabe Yo
Major pharmaceutical companies and university hospitals are attempting to research and develop a drug for dementia, something that remains an elusive goal.
However, it's becoming clearer that dementia and lifestyle are related, and it has been discovered that it is possible to keep it at bay so that it does not advance past a merely forgetful level, and the symptoms are negligible.
I spoke to Professor Otsuki Shunsuke at the Kinki University Hospital Stroke Centre to find out more.
Dementia never fully goes away
A cure or prevention for dementia has been long-awaited, but what is the current state of progress?
Otsuki: As we age, it's possible for anyone to suffer from dementia, though there are varying degrees of severity, from mild to quite serious indeed.
However, it is thought that it will still take more than twenty years before a novel dementia drug is developed.
Donepezil, the drug commonly used in Japan, is already not covered by insurance, so we can't hope for it to be a miraculous cure.
Meanwhile, people can now live longer lives thanks to fewer deaths from infectious diseases and accidents, and deaths from cancer are also decreasing thanks to the startling progress that has been made in anti-cancer treatments.
Because of that, the fact is that cases of dementia are on the rise.
It's not a problem that can be solved by the individual and their family alone, it's also necessary for society as a whole to create an environment so that they can live safely in the community.
How to keep dementia at a "forgetful" level
Are there any kinds of people who are more prone to dementia, or who are less likely to get it?
Otsuki: Even if dementia is not completely avoidable, it is possible to suppress the symptoms to the extent that it is nothing more than forgetfulness.
Dementia is considered a lifestyle-related disease and there are certain trends among people who are more prone.
Firstly, overweight people are far more likely to get dementia.
Dementia is treated as a lifestyle-related disease.
It is a combination of obesity, high blood pressure, diabetes and high cholesterol.
Finances are also a factor.
For example, in some parts of the US, food stamps are given out to the poorer members of society, and the foods that you can receive with food stamps are things with a long shelf life such as frozen hamburgers, pizza and chicken.
They can be used by people who live in an environment where they cannot cook in the first place, because they don't have gas or electricity.
This results in a diet that is low in vegetables and protein, leading to an unbalanced lifestyle that is high in fat and sugar.
Eventually, they end up poor but obese, with nothing to do but tune out in front of the TV, and they become physically impaired.
I believe a similar situation could exist in Japan.
Also, people who don't have anything to think about, or who don't work, tend to be more prone to dementia.
In other words, it's important to not become obese and to read books and consider things regularly to stave off dementia.
